<emphasis box="[1271,1364,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="101">Q. roma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on the following characters: sparse punctation of abdomen; apical portion of the median lobe of the aedeagus (in parameral or anteparameral view) broad and not pointed, (in lateral view) with minute tooth and carina basally from the tooth; wide paramere with 10–12 sensory peg setae divided in two elongate groups by apical emargination. Nevertheless, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2018" box="[480,631,512,535]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="repentinus">
<emphasis box="[480,631,512,535]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="101">Q. repentinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Solodovnikov et Hansen" authorityYear="2016" box="[1035,1131,512,536]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="roma">
<emphasis box="[1035,1131,512,536]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="101">Q. roma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
externally by a relatively wider head and the shape of the pronotum with less pronounced posterior angles and the lateral contours less narrowing anteriad before anterior angles. Also, compared to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Solodovnikov et Hansen" authorityYear="2016" box="[890,989,584,608]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="roma">
<emphasis box="[890,989,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="101">Q. roma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2018" box="[1208,1360,584,607]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="repentinus">
<emphasis box="[1208,1360,584,607]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="101">Q. repentinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a narrower apex of the median lobe (in lateral view), a deeper apical emargination of the paramere (in parameral view), and a less defined arrangement of sensory peg setae extending to the lateral margins of the paramere (in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Solodovnikov et Hansen" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="roma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="101">Q. roma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forming compact groups at apex only).
</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,1175,1746,1768]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1196950/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="101" startId="6.[151,250,1746,1768]" targetBox="[151,1436,773,1725]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1175,1746,1768]" box="[151,1175,1746,1768]" pageId="6" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1746,1768]" pageId="6" pageNumber="101">FIGURE 4.</emphasis>
Typical talus-associated habitat at Mt. Evrechala (SE Altai). Photo by I.I. Lubechanskiy.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1812,2018]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1436,151,680]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="102" pageId="6" pageNumber="101">
Both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2018" box="[260,412,1813,1837]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="repentinus">
<emphasis box="[260,412,1813,1837]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="101">Q. repentinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Solodovnikov et Hansen" authorityYear="2016" box="[467,560,1813,1837]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="roma">
<emphasis box="[467,560,1813,1837]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="101">Q. roma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
share some characters with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Riittir" authorityYear="1887" box="[878,1040,1813,1837]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="przewalskii">
<emphasis box="[878,1040,1813,1837]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="101">Q. przewalskii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: posterior frontal puncture situated at about the same distance from posterior margin of eye and nuchal ridge; three punctures in each dorsal row of the pronotum and one to two in the sublateral row; posteriorly explanate lateral portions of pronotum; impunctate glabrous scutellum; an asymmetrical aedeagus (best seen in parameral view) with the median lobe (in lateral view) having a subapical tooth and the paramere (in parameral view) with a shallow apical emargination and a similar pattern of peg setae. Since the diagnosis and composition of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Riittir" authorityYear="1887" box="[918,1083,1993,2017]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="przewalskii">
<emphasis box="[918,1083,1993,2017]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="101">Q. przewalskii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group remain unclear (
<bibRefCitation box="[158,511,151,176]" pageId="7" pageNumber="102" refId="ref5113" refString="Solodovnikov, A. &amp; Hansen, A. K. (2016) Review of subterranean Quedius, with description of the first hypogean species from the Russian Far East (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Staphylinini). Zootaxa, 4170 (3), 475 - 490. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4170.3.3" type="journal article">Solodovnikov &amp; Hansen, 2016</bibRefCitation>
), both species can be affiliated with this group only tentatively. Both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2018" box="[1284,1435,152,175]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="repentinus">
<emphasis box="[1284,1435,152,175]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">Q. repentinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Solodovnikov et Hansen" authorityYear="2016" box="[200,294,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="roma">
<emphasis box="[200,294,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">Q. roma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Riittir" authorityYear="1887" box="[679,842,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="przewalskii">
<emphasis box="[679,842,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">Q. przewalskii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by longer elytra, sparse punctation of the abdomen, and by the structure of aedeagus, in particular by a wider paramere with more stretched arrangement of peg setae and a blunt median lobe with a carina basally from the subapical tooth facing the paramere.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,680]" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">
Even though 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2018" box="[355,510,296,319]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="repentinus">
<emphasis box="[355,510,296,319]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">Q. repentinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also resembles the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eppelsheim A.Smetana" authorityYear="1888" box="[744,886,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mutilatus">
<emphasis box="[744,886,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">Q. mutilatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group due to shared adaptations to the hypogean biology and is generally similar to the latter in habitus and chaetotaxy of head and pronotum, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="repentinus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">Q. repentinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(and its presumed sister species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Solodovnikov et Hansen" authorityYear="2016" box="[644,738,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="roma">
<emphasis box="[644,738,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">Q. roma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) seem more remote from that group. Unlike the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eppelsheim A.Smetana" authorityYear="1888" box="[1296,1436,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mutilatus">
<emphasis box="[1296,1436,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">Q. mutilatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group they have the posterior frontal puncture situated farther away from the nuchal ridge and a different structure of the aedeagus, which in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eppelsheim A.Smetana" authorityYear="1888" box="[548,686,440,464]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mutilatus">
<emphasis box="[548,686,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">Q. mutilatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group is symmetric, with a differently shaped apical portion of the median lobe and the paramere having four groups of sensory peg setae (two apical and two subapical).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="102" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,680]" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,544,511,536]" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">Distribution and bionomics.</emphasis>
So far 
<taxonomicName authority="Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov, 2018" authorityName="Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2018" box="[643,866,512,536]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="repentinus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[643,866,512,536]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">Quedius repentinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[878,948,511,536]" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[878,948,511,536]" pageId="7" pageNumber="102" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[1257,1305,512,536]" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">type</typeStatus>
locality in Evrechala Mountain in the southeastern 
<collectingRegion box="[601,661,548,573]" country="Russia" name="Altay" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">Altai</collectingRegion>
. The specimens were collected at an elevation of 
<quantity box="[1212,1367,548,573]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.95" metricValueMax="2.05" metricValueMin="1.85" pageId="7" pageNumber="102" unit="m" value="1950.0" valueMax="2050.0" valueMin="1850.0">1850–2050 m</quantity>
in the old talus already covered by the ground or fine detrital rock with lichens (
<figureCitation box="[976,1046,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1746,1768]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,773,1725]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,772,1725]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Typical talus-associated habitat at Mt.Evrechala (SE Altai). Photo by I.I. Lubechanskiy." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1196950/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="102" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,680]" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,620,645]" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name is the Latin adjective ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2018" box="[731,848,621,644]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="repentinus">
<emphasis box="[731,848,621,644]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">repentinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ (= 
<emphasis box="[893,1019,620,644]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">unexpected</emphasis>
) that refers to the fact that the new species appears phylogenetically close to the geographically remote 
<emphasis box="[917,1016,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="102">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Solodovnikov et Hansen" authorityYear="2016" box="[917,1013,656,680]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="roma">Q. roma</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
which was unexpected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
